  "chunk_index": 35,
  "summary": "George Lomax visits Lord Kettlemere to ask for permission to marry Eileen Bündel. Lord Kettlemere advises George to reconsider to avoid potential rejection and instructs his butler, Tredewell, to summon Bündel to the living room to speak with George. After George departs, Bill Everleigh arrives at the estate seeking Bündel. When Lord Kettlemere informs Bill that George is currently proposing to her, Bill becomes enraged, insulting George as a shameless hypocrite and expressing regret that he never proposed to Bündel himself. Distraught, Bill drives to London to visit Jimmy Sycamore at St. James Square.\n\nBill tells Jimmy that he is deeply unsettled by a letter he received from the executor of Ronnie DeVille's will, which was scheduled to be sent two weeks after DeVille's death. Although Bill initially appears bewildered and shaken, he regains his composure after drinking whiskey. Once Jimmy sends his servant, Stevens, out to buy cigarettes to ensure privacy, Bill prepares to reveal the baffling contents of the letter.\n\nMeanwhile, Bündel returns to the garden in a state of distress. She informs Lorelai that George Lomax has proposed to her, expressing her frustration and hatred for his stuttering, nonsensical proposal and noting that she does not know how to respond.",
